column1: # Every CPU automatically has PAPI_TOT_CYC and PAPI_TOT_INS added
# The processor identifier *can not* contain any comma characters as these
#    This definition give an accurate count of the instructions retired through the FP unit
#    It counts just about everything except MMX and 3DNow instructions

column2: it also counts loads and stores. Therefore the count will be uniformly
but proportional to the work done.

column1: #/*  This definition is speculative but gives good answers on our simple test cases

column3: but doesn't count loads and stores

column6: 'Counts speculative adds and multiplies. Variable and higher than theoretical.'
Counts all retired floating point operations, including data movement. Precise, and proportional to work done, but much higher than theoretical.
Counts speculative adds and multiplies. Variable and higher than theoretical.

column7: Counts retired ops corrected for data motion. Optimized for single precision; lower than theoretical.
Counts retired ops corrected for data motion. Optimized for double precision; lower than theoretical.

column1: #    This definition is identical for both FP_INS and FP_OPS
#    An analysis by Bill Homer of Cray indicates accurate counts over a range of conditions

column6: Counts both divide and square root instructions
Counts both divide and square root instructions

column1: # This is an alternate definition of OPS that produces no error with calibrate
# the previous definition was identical to FP_INS
# This is an example of multiple processor names matching the same table

column7: PAPI_FP_INS counts only retired x87 uops tagged with 0. If you add other native events tagged with 0, their counts will be included in PAPI_FP_INS
PAPI_FP_OPS counts retired x87 uops tagged with 1.
PAPI_FP_OPS counts retired scalar_SP SSE uops tagged with 1.
PAPI_FP_OPS counts retired scalar_DP SSE uops tagged with 1.

column8: PAPI_FP_OPS counts retired x87 and scalar_SP SSE uops tagged with 1.
PAPI_FP_OPS counts retired x87 and scalar_DP SSE uops tagged with 1.
PAPI_FP_OPS counts retired scalar_SP and scalar_DP SSE uops tagged with 1.
PAPI_VEC_INS counts retired 64bit and 128bit MMX uops tagged with 2.

PAPI_VEC_INS counts retired packed single and double precision SSE uops tagged with 2.
